ical scrutiny of the Weimar jurisprudence of crisis offers an invaluable overview of the perils and promise of constitutional development in states that lack an entrenched tradition of constitutionalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aConstitutional historyxSourcesxGermany. 0aConstitutional historyzGermanyvSources. 0aConstitutional historyzGermanyxHistoryvSources. 0aConstitutional historyzGermanyxHistoryxPhilosophyvSources. 0aConstitutional lawxSourcesxPhilosophyxHistoryxGermany. 0aConstitutional lawzGermanyxPhilosophyxHistoryvSources. 0aState, ThevSources. 0aState, ThexHistoryvSources. 0aState, ThexSourcesxHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aconstitution.  aconstitutional amendment.  aconstitutional.  acrisis.  ademocracy.  ademocratic republic.  aethics.  aeuropean history.  aformalism.  agerman history.  agermany.  alaw.  alegal issues.  alegal theory.  aphilosophy.  apolitical.  apolitics.  asocial change.  asocial justice.  asocial studies.  asocial theory.  asocial transformation.  asociology.  aweimar constitution.  aworld history.1 aAnschütz, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Peter C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCloyd, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDyzenhaus, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForsthoff, Ernst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeller, Hermann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuber, Ernst Rudolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHöhn, Reinhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a